english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Moonlight
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lee, the Junior Administrator, came to me and said: "My father has retired from office and spends his twilight years in Kaeryong. To the west of his dwelling, he has built a small chamber where he sits in stillness, his heart turned toward the Western Paradise, his lips ever chanting the name of that world's Master. Long has he devoted himself thus, garbed as a true follower of the Buddha's way. Yet still he drinks wine and cherishes his guests as he did in former days. Though the Master cannot visit him there, my father's thoughts of the Master never rest. Should I obtain one word from the Master to hang upon the wall of his hall, it would be as though my father faced the Master daily, and might ease somewhat his yearning heart. I humbly ask that you name this place and expound its meaning."

    I replied: "Your father is one with whom I have wandered in joy. His disdain for the world and noble aspiration surpass even the great sages of old—such is the fate of a man of good lineage whose official fortune has remained modest. Let me observe the situation before us. Broad plains and great rivers spread below, while Gold Turtle Mountain rises to the south, and Straight Finger Peak stands to the west. To the northeast, lesser peaks bow humbly beneath the eaves. Before the hall, a pond has been excavated and lotus flowers and willows planted, embodying both the illusory paradise he yearns for and the hermit's solitude he seeks. The illusory paradise is what we call the Western Pure Land, while the hermit's life recalls the great recluse Tao Yuanming of the Jin. Standing by flowing water, gazing at the moon, one's spirit and joy become boundless. Even we Confucian scholars cannot match the harmony between this father and son. Though his heart turns toward renunciation and the Western Buddha's realm, he upholds our great moral way, nurturing filial piety and compassion, and bringing goodness to his village—of this we can be certain. The Hall of Moonlight must have its record.

    Long have I been ill, seeking retirement to spend my final years in Hamchang, yet this wish remains unfulfilled. Should Heaven's blessing grant me this desire, I shall travel these hundred leagues of mountains and streams on horseback, a cup of wine and moonlight my companions, there to recount the old joy of wandering together. I shall compose a grand poem on the Hall of Moonlight to sing your father's praise. As I pause with cup in hand, I ask one thing: might the spirit who guides the moon slow its passage, if only briefly?

    Your name is Ang, I recall, and you are my kinsman by marriage. Thus I write this record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Western Paradise (西方) refers to Amitabha Buddha's Pure Land in Buddhist cosmology, the focus of devotional practice in East Asian Buddhism.
  - key: ''
    value: Tao Yuanming (陶淵明), known as the supreme hermit-recluse of Chinese poetry, exemplifies the Confucian scholar who withdrew from service while maintaining moral integrity.
  - key: ''
    value: The Hall of Moonlight serves as both a literal viewing pavilion and a metaphorical space where Buddhist aspiration and Confucian virtue harmonize.
